21 RECREATIONAL BOATING SAFETY CONFORMING PROGRAM CHANGES
22 SECTION 3.(a) G.S. 75A-5 reads as rewritten:
23 "§ 75A-5. Application for certificate of number; fees; reciprocity; change of ownership;
24 conformity with federal regulations; records; award of certificates; renewal of
25 certificates; transfer of partial interest; destroyed or junked vessels;
26 abandonment; change of address; duplicate certificates; display.
27 …
28 (b) Reciprocity. – The owner of any vessel already covered by a number in full force and
29 effect pursuant to federal law or a federally approved numbering system of another state shall
30 record the identification number prior to operating the vessel on the waters of this State in excess
31 of the 90-day 60-day reciprocity period provided for in G.S. 75A-7(a)(1). The recordation shall
32 be made pursuant to subsection (a) of this section, except that no additional or substitute
33 identification number shall be issued.
34 …."
35 SECTION 3.(b) G.S. 75A-7(a) reads as rewritten:
36 "(a) A vessel shall not be required to be numbered under this Chapter if it is:
37 (1) A vessel that is required to be awarded an identification number pursuant to
38 federal law or a federally approved numbering system of another state, and
39 for which an identification number has been so awarded: Provided, that any
40 such vessel shall not have been within this State for a period in excess of 90
41 60 consecutive days.
42 …."
43 SECTION 3.(c) G.S. 75A-6.1(a) reads as rewritten:
44 "(a) Every vessel operated on the waters of this State that is required to obtain an
45 identification number pursuant to this Chapter, has a valid marine document issued by the federal
46 Bureau of Customs or any federal agency successor to it, or issued pursuant to a federally
47 approved numbering system of another state shall comply with the navigation rules, including
48 requirements for navigational lights, sound-signaling devices, and other equipment, contained in
49 the Inland Navigational Rules Act of 1980, codified as amended at 33 U.S.C. §§ 2001-2038,
50 2071-2073 (1993) and rules adopted pursuant thereto, see 33 C.F.R. Part 84 (1992)."
51 SECTION 3.(d) G.S. 75A-13.3 reads as rewritten:
Page 2 House Bill 747-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 75A-13.3. Personal watercraft.
2 …
3 (d) No person shall operate a personal watercraft on the waters of this State, nor shall the
4 owner of a personal watercraft knowingly allow another person to operate that personal
5 watercraft on the waters of this State, unless:
6 (1) Each person riding on or being towed behind the vessel is wearing a personal
7 flotation device approved by the United States Coast Guard. Inflatable
8 personal flotation devices do not satisfy this requirement; and
9 (2) In the case of a personal watercraft equipped by the manufacturer with a
10 lanyard-type an engine cut-off switch, the lanyard is securely attached to the
11 person, clothing, or flotation device of the operator at all times while the
12 personal watercraft is being operated in such a manner to turn off the engine
13 if the operator dismounts while the watercraft is in operation.the engine
14 cut-off switch is being used while the vessel is operating on plane or above
15 displacement speed.
16 …
17 (e) A personal watercraft must at all times be operated in a reasonable and prudent
18 manner. Maneuvers that endanger life, limb, or property shall constitute reckless operation of a
19 vessel as provided in G.S. 75A-10, and include any of the following:
20 (1) Unreasonably or unnecessarily weaving through congested vessel traffic.
21 (2) Jumping the wake of another vessel within 100 feet of the other vessel or when
22 visibility around the other vessel is obstructed.
23 (3) Intentionally approaching another vessel in order to swerve at the last possible
24 moment to avoid collision.
25 (4) Repealed by Session Laws 2000-52, s. 2.
26 (5) Operating contrary to the "rules of the road" navigation rules or following too
27 closely to another vessel, including another personal watercraft. For purposes
28 of this subdivision, "following too closely" means proceeding in the same
29 direction and operating at a speed in excess of 10 miles per hour when
30 approaching within 100 feet to the rear or 50 feet to the side of another vessel
31 that is underway unless that vessel is operating in a narrow channel, in which
32 case a personal watercraft may operate at the speed and flow of other vessel
33 traffic.
34 …."
35 SECTION 3.(e) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025. Prosecutions for
36 offenses committed before the effective date of this act are not abated or affected by this act, and
37 the statutes that would be applicable but for this act remain applicable to those prosecutions.
38
39 EFFECTIVE DATE
40 SECTION 4. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
41 law.
